physical_examinations.relevant_findings: Physical examination revealed multiple, palpable, bilateral breast nodules, all measuring less than 1 cm. After completion of breastfeeding, there were no palpable masses, skin changes, nipple retraction, or suggestive adenopathy.
physical_examinations.changes_over_time: Initially, after the first month of breastfeeding, the patient noted a thickening in the upper outer quadrant of her left breast, which later evolved to bilateral obstructed milk ducts recurrently. After cessation of breastfeeding, the findings improved, revealing no significant abnormalities.

physical_examinations.relevant_findings: Bilateral normal physical examination of the breast revealed no focal masses in the regions of the calcifications or elsewhere; hypercalcemia and hyperparathyroidism were excluded based on normal levels of serum calcium and parathyroid hormone.
